{{Template:USMC-History}}
The '''[[w:military history|history]] of the [[w:United States Marine Corps|United States Marine Corps]]''' began with the founding of the [[w:Continental Marines|Continental Marines]] in [[w:1775|1775]] to conduct ship-to-ship fighting, provide shipboard security and discipline enforcement, and assist in landing forces. Its mission evolved with changing military doctrine and foreign policy of the [[w:United States|United States]]. Owing to the availability of Marine forces at sea, the United States Marine Corps has served in nearly every conflict in [[w:History of the United States|United States history]]. It attained prominence when its theories and practice of [[w:amphibious warfare|amphibious warfare]] proved prescient, and ultimately formed a cornerstone of the [[w:Pacific Theater of Operations|Pacific Theater]] of [[w:World War II|World War II]].
By the early [[w:20th century|20th century]], the Marine Corps would become one of the dominant theorists and practitioners of amphibious warfare. Its ability to [[w:rapid deployment force|rapidly respond]] on short notice to [[w:expeditionary warfare|expeditionary crises]] has made and continues to make it an important tool for [[w:foreign policy of the United States|American foreign policy]].<ref name="forwardfromthesea">{{cite paper|author=[[w:John Howard Dalton|John Howard Dalton]], [[w:United States Secretary of the Navy|Secretary of the Navy]]; [[w:Jeremy Michael Boorda|Jeremy Michael Boorda]], [[w:Chief of Naval Operations|Chief of Naval Operations]]; [[w:Carl E. Mundy|Carl E. Mundy]], [[w:Commandant of the Marine Corps|Commandant of the Marine Corps]]|title=Forward... From the Sea|publisher=[[w:United States Department of the Navy]]|date=9 November 1994|url=http://www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/policy/fromsea/forward.txt}}</ref>
